<DocsLayout title="Access Control Overview">
  <h1>Access Control (ACL)</h1>
  <p>EntDB includes inheritance-based access control as a built-in database feature. Every read is automatically filtered by the requesting actor's permissions. Your application never needs to implement permission checking &mdash; the database does it transparently.</p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>Every node has an access control entry. Access is determined by four paths, checked in order:</p>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Path</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Owner</strong></td><td>Node creator always has ADMIN</td><td><code>owner_actor = "user:alice"</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Direct grant</strong></td><td>Explicit share via <code>node_access</code></td><td><code>db.share(node_id, "user:bob", "write")</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Group</strong></td><td>Access via group membership</td><td>Bob is in <code>group:eng</code>, group has READ</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Inheritance</strong></td><td>Access via structural parent</td><td>Comment inherits from Task via <code>propagate_share</code></td></tr>
  </table>

  <p>If any path grants access, the actor can see the node. An explicit <strong>DENY</strong> on the specific node overrides all inherited access.</p>

  <h2>Inheritance: The Key Feature</h2>
  <p>When you share a task with Bob, he can automatically see all comments on that task. You don't need to share each comment individually.</p>

  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Define structural edge
HasComment = EdgeTypeDef(
    edge_id=1, name="HasComment",
    from_type=Task, to_type=Comment,
    propagate_share=True,  # THIS is what enables inheritance
)

# Share the task
await db.share(task_id, "user:bob", "read", tenant_id, granted_by="user:alice")

# Bob can now see ALL comments on the task
comments = await db.connected(task_id, HasComment, tenant_id, actor="user:bob")
# Returns all comments - no per-comment permission check needed`}
    go={`// Edge type defined in .proto with propagate_share=true (registered via codegen).

// Share the task
alice := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("alice"))
if err := alice.Share(ctx, taskID, entdb.UserActor("bob"), entdb.PermissionRead); err != nil {
    return err
}

// Bob can now see ALL comments on the task
bob := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("bob"))
comments, err := bob.EdgesFrom(ctx, taskID, shop.HasCommentEdgeID)
// Returns all comments — no per-comment permission check needed`}
  />

  <h3>How inheritance works internally</h3>
  <p>When a structural edge is created (<code>propagate_share=True</code>), an <code>acl_inherit</code> row is inserted:</p>
  <Code code={`# Creating an edge: task_1 → comment_42 (HasComment, propagate_share=True)
# Internally inserts: acl_inherit(node_id="comment_42", inherit_from="task_1")

# Access check for comment_42:
# 1. Check comment_42 directly → not found
# 2. Walk acl_inherit chain: comment_42 → task_1
# 3. Check task_1: Bob has READ via node_access → ALLOWED`} lang="yaml" />

  <h3>Deep inheritance</h3>
  <p>Inheritance chains can be multiple levels deep:</p>
  <Code code={`# project → task → comment (3 levels)
# Share project with Bob → Bob can see all tasks AND all comments`} lang="plaintext" />

  <h3>New nodes inherit automatically</h3>
  <p>If you add a comment to a task AFTER sharing the task, the new comment is immediately accessible. No backfill needed.</p>

  <h3>Revoke cascades automatically</h3>
  <p>Revoking Bob's access to the task automatically blocks access to all comments. No cascade delete of permissions needed.</p>

  <h2>Private Nodes</h2>
  <p>Some node types should never inherit from parents &mdash; grades, drafts, moderator notes:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`Grade = NodeTypeDef(
    type_id=10, name="Grade",
    fields=(field(1, "score", "int", required=True),),
    acl_defaults=AclDefaults(
        inherit=False,         # PRIVATE: no acl_inherit row created
        tenant_visible=False,  # not visible to all tenant members
    ),
)
# Grade is only visible to its owner and explicit direct grants`}
    goNote={`In Go, "private" node behaviour is configured at the schema layer (proto entdb.node options: inherit=false, tenant_visible=false), not in client code. Once the proto is registered with the codegen'd type, the Go SDK simply respects it on read.`}
  />

  <h2>Permissions</h2>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Permission</th><th>Grants</th><th>Use Case</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>read</code></td><td>Read node payload</td><td>Viewer</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>comment</code></td><td>Read + add comment children</td><td>Commenter</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>write</code></td><td>Read + Comment + update payload</td><td>Editor</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>share</code></td><td>Read + Comment + Write + reshare</td><td>Collaborator</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>delete</code></td><td>Read + Comment + Write + delete</td><td>Manager</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>admin</code></td><td>All permissions</td><td>Owner</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>deny</code></td><td>Blocks all access</td><td>Explicit block</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>Higher permissions include lower ones. <code>admin</code> includes everything. <code>deny</code> overrides everything (except owner).</p>

  <h2>Receiving Shared Nodes</h2>
  <p>The flip side of <code>share()</code>: list every node that other actors have shared with you. Use it to render an "Inbox" or "Shared with me" surface. Pagination is plain offset/limit:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# First page (default limit=100)
inbox = await db.shared_with_me("acme", actor="user:bob")

# Subsequent pages
page2 = await db.shared_with_me("acme", actor="user:bob",
                                limit=50, offset=50)

for node in inbox:
    print(node.node_id, node.type_id)`}
    goNote="ListSharedWithMe is on the gRPC wire (EntDBService.ListSharedWithMe) but no convenience helper exists on the Go Scope yet. Call the generated client directly via internal/pb until the wrapper lands."
  />

  <h2>Revoking Access</h2>
  <p><code>revoke()</code> removes a single direct grant from <code>node_access</code>. It returns <code>True</code> only if a grant actually existed:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`existed = await db.revoke(
    node_id=task_id,
    actor_id="user:bob",          # the grantee being revoked
    tenant_id="acme",
    actor="user:alice",            # the actor performing the revoke
)
# If task → comments has propagate_share=True, Bob's access to the
# comments disappears with the same call — inheritance is computed
# at read time, no cascade rows to clean up.`}
    goNote="Revoke is wire-supported (EntDBService.RevokeAccess) but the Go Scope helper has not landed yet. Call the generated client directly until then."
  />
  <p>
    Revoke only undoes <em>direct</em> grants on the named node. If Bob still
    has access via a group, a higher-level structural parent (with
    <code>propagate_share=True</code>), or a public/tenant-visible default,
    those paths remain — revoke the appropriate parent or remove the group
    membership instead.
  </p>

  <h2>Groups</h2>
  <p>Groups are a way to share with multiple users at once. Groups can contain users and other groups (nested):</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Add users to groups
await db.group_add("group:eng", "user:alice", tenant_id)
await db.group_add("group:eng", "user:bob", tenant_id)

# Nested groups
await db.group_add("group:all-staff", "group:eng", tenant_id)

# Share with group — all members get access
await db.share(task_id, "group:eng", "write", tenant_id, granted_by="user:alice")`}
    go={`scope := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("alice"))

// Add users to groups
scope.AddGroupMember(ctx, "group:eng", entdb.UserActor("alice"), "member")
scope.AddGroupMember(ctx, "group:eng", entdb.UserActor("bob"),   "member")

// Nested groups
scope.AddGroupMember(ctx, "group:all-staff", entdb.GroupActor("eng"), "member")

// Share with the group — all members get access
scope.Share(ctx, taskID, entdb.GroupActor("eng"), entdb.PermissionWrite)`}
  />

  <h3>Worked example: group lifecycle</h3>
  <p>Create a group, add two members, share with the group, then drop one member &mdash; the dropped member loses access immediately on the next read:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`tenant = "acme"
admin  = "user:alice"

# 1. Populate the group
await db.group_add("group:reviewers", "user:bob",   tenant, actor=admin)
await db.group_add("group:reviewers", "user:carol", tenant, actor=admin)

# 2. Share a doc with the whole group
await db.share(doc_id, "group:reviewers", tenant, admin,
               permission="write", actor_type="group")

# Bob and Carol can both read+write the doc.
assert await db.get(Doc, doc_id, tenant, "user:bob")  is not None
assert await db.get(Doc, doc_id, tenant, "user:carol") is not None

# 3. Remove Carol from the group
await db.group_remove("group:reviewers", "user:carol", tenant, actor=admin)

# 4. Carol's access is gone on the next read; Bob is unaffected.
assert await db.get(Doc, doc_id, tenant, "user:carol") is None
assert await db.get(Doc, doc_id, tenant, "user:bob")  is not None`}
    go={`adminScope := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("alice"))

// 1. Populate the group
adminScope.AddGroupMember(ctx, "group:reviewers", entdb.UserActor("bob"),   "member")
adminScope.AddGroupMember(ctx, "group:reviewers", entdb.UserActor("carol"), "member")

// 2. Share a doc with the whole group
adminScope.Share(ctx, docID, entdb.GroupActor("reviewers"), entdb.PermissionWrite)

// Bob and Carol can both read+write the doc.
bobScope   := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("bob"))
carolScope := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("carol"))
_, _ = entdb.Get[*shop.Doc](ctx, bobScope, docID)
_, _ = entdb.Get[*shop.Doc](ctx, carolScope, docID)

// 3. Remove Carol from the group
adminScope.RemoveGroupMember(ctx, "group:reviewers", entdb.UserActor("carol"))

// 4. Carol's access is gone on the next read; Bob is unaffected.
carolDoc, _ := entdb.Get[*shop.Doc](ctx, carolScope, docID) // nil
bobDoc,   _ := entdb.Get[*shop.Doc](ctx, bobScope,   docID) // still readable`}
  />

  <h2>Capability-Based ACL</h2>
  <p>
    Beyond the universal <code>read / write / admin</code> ladder, EntDB
    supports <strong>typed capabilities</strong> declared per node type. This
    lets you model domain roles like "Approver" or "Auditor" that grant a
    specific, narrow operation rather than a broad permission level.
  </p>
  <p>The shape is two pieces in your <code>.proto</code>:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      An enum that lists the per-type extension capabilities, named on the
      node via
      <code>(entdb.node).extension_capability_enum = "TaskExtCapability"</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      A list of
      <code>CapabilityMapping</code>
      entries on the node mapping a server op (and optionally a field, field
      value, or child type) to the capability required to perform it.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <Code code={`// schema.proto
import "entdb_options.proto";

enum TaskExtCapability {
  TASK_EXT_CAP_UNSPECIFIED = 0;
  TASK_EXT_CAP_APPROVE     = 1;   // can flip status -> "approved"
  TASK_EXT_CAP_REOPEN      = 2;   // can flip status -> "reopened"
}

message Task {
  option (entdb.node) = {
    type_id: 30
    extension_capability_enum: "TaskExtCapability"
    capability_mappings: [
      // UpdateNode on field "status" with value "approved"
      // requires the per-type APPROVE capability.
      { op: "UpdateNode" field: "status" field_value: "approved"
        required_ext: 1 },
      { op: "UpdateNode" field: "status" field_value: "reopened"
        required_ext: 2 }
    ]
  };

  string title  = 1 [(entdb.field).required = true];
  string status = 2;
}`} lang="proto" />
  <p>
    With this in place, an actor who only holds
    <code>TASK_EXT_CAP_APPROVE</code> can flip <code>status</code> to
    <code>"approved"</code> but cannot change the title or any other field
    &mdash; the server consults the mapping table on every
    <code>UpdateNode</code> and rejects ops the actor lacks the typed
    capability for. Field-level mappings take precedence over type-wide
    mappings, and built-in implications (<code>ADMIN > EDIT > COMMENT >
    READ</code>) still apply.
  </p>
  <p>
    Grant a typed capability the same way you grant a core permission &mdash;
    via the share RPC, passing the extension capability id alongside any
    core caps you also want to bestow. See
    <code>proto/entdb_options.proto</code> for the full
    <code>CapabilityMapping</code> / <code>CapabilityImplication</code>
    schema.
  </p>

  <h2>Deny Rules</h2>
  <p>Explicit deny overrides all inherited access:</p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Bob has write on task (and all comments via inheritance)
await db.share(task_id, "user:bob", "write", tenant_id, granted_by="user:alice")

# But this specific comment is confidential
await db.share(confidential_comment_id, "user:bob", "deny", tenant_id, granted_by="user:alice")
# Bob can see the task and all other comments, but NOT this one`}
    go={`alice := client.Tenant("acme").Actor(entdb.UserActor("alice"))

// Bob has write on task (and all comments via inheritance)
alice.Share(ctx, taskID, entdb.UserActor("bob"), entdb.PermissionWrite)

// But this specific comment is confidential
alice.Share(ctx, confidentialCommentID, entdb.UserActor("bob"), entdb.PermissionDeny)
// Bob can see the task and all other comments, but NOT this one`}
  />

  <h2>Cycle Prevention</h2>
  <p>The applier detects and rejects cycles in the <code>acl_inherit</code> chain at data insertion time. For example, if Folder A contains Folder B, and you try to make B contain A, the cycle is detected and the edge creation is rejected. A depth limit of 10 in the recursive CTE provides a backstop at query time.</p>

